<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-circumscribed-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Circumscribed Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                            <ul>
                              <li>Construct an inscribed, circumscribed and escribed circles on a triangle</li>
                              <li>Determine the centroid and orthocentre of a triangle</li>
                            </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover the circumcenter by asking: <em>can you draw a circle that passes through all three vertices of a triangle?</em>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Let learners attempt part (a) with trial and error — most will not find the right centre immediately, and that frustration motivates the reasoning in part (c). When circulating, prompt with: <q>If the circle must pass through both A and B, where could the centre be?</q> and <q>What if it also has to pass through C?</q> The key insight is that the centre must be equidistant from all three vertices, so it lies on the perpendicular bisector of every side.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>A Circle Through All Three Vertices</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will investigate whether a circle can pass through all three vertices of a triangle, and how to find its centre.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> of your choice using a ruler. Using a compass, try to draw a circle that passes exactly through all three vertices. Mark the centre you used. (You may need several attempts!)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare with a classmate. Did you choose the same centre? Whose circle passes more accurately through all three vertices?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Reason about where the centre must be. The circle passes through <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, so the centre is equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. What is the set of all points equidistant from two given points? Where must the centre also lie because the circle passes through <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The set of points equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>. Similarly for <m>B</m> and <m>C</m>. The centre lies on both perpendicular bisectors, so it must be their intersection.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m> using compasses and a ruler. Then construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m>. Label their intersection <m>O</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Measure <m>OA</m>, <m>OB</m>, and <m>OC</m>. Record them in the table below. Draw a circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>OA</m>. Does it pass through all three vertices?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The three distances should be equal up to measurement error. The circle passes through all three vertices — this confirms that <m>O</m> is equidistant from all three vertices.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Distances from circumcenter to vertices</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Triangle</cell>
                            <cell><m>OA</m> (mm)</cell>
                            <cell><m>OB</m> (mm)</cell>
                            <cell><m>OC</m> (mm)</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>2</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>3</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the circumcenter construction and discuss how its position changes with the type of triangle.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Ask learners to share their distances. Confirm they are (approximately) equal. Tell learners: <q>This point <m>O</m> is called the <term>circumcenter</term>. The circle centred at <m>O</m> that passes through all three vertices is the <term>circumscribed circle</term>, or <term>circumcircle</term>, and its radius <m>R</m> is the <term>circumradius</term>.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Ask: <q>Was <m>O</m> inside or outside your triangle? Did everyone's triangle give the same answer?</q> Draw attention to the fact that the position of <m>O</m> depends on whether the triangle is acute, right, or obtuse.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For a right triangle, <m>O</m> always falls at the midpoint of the hypotenuse — learners can verify this with their own diagram.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-circumscribed-circle">
        <title>The Circumcircle and Circumradius</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The three perpendicular bisectors of the sides of any triangle meet at a single point <m>O</m>, called the <term>circumcenter</term>. The circle centred at <m>O</m> passing through all three vertices is the <term>circumscribed circle</term> (or <term>circumcircle</term>). Its radius, the <term>circumradius</term> <m>R</m>, satisfies
                <md>
                    R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \text{Area}},
                </md>
                where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m> are the side lengths of the triangle.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circumcircle-thm">
                <caption>The circumcircle of triangle <m>ABC</m>. The three perpendicular bisectors (grey) meet at circumcenter <m>O</m>, which is equidistant from all three vertices: <m>OA = OB = OC = R</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 2.5/4/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MAC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawLines[gray!55, thin, add=0.8 and 0.8](MAB,O)(MBC,O)(MAC,O)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[dashed, red!60!black](O,A)(O,B)(O,C)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](B,MBC,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](A,MAC,O)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,A)(O,B)(O,C)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[pos=0.55, left](O,C){$R$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                Let <m>O</m> be the intersection of the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m> and the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m>. Since <m>O</m> lies on the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>, it is equidistant from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>: <m>OA = OB</m>. Since <m>O</m> lies on the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m>, we have <m>OB = OC</m>. Therefore <m>OA = OB = OC</m>, so the circle with centre <m>O</m> and radius <m>R = OA</m> passes through all three vertices.
            </p>
            <p>
                The formula <m>R = abc/(4 \cdot \text{Area})</m> follows from the extended law of sines: <m>a/\sin A = 2R</m>, combined with the formula Area <m>= \tfrac{1}{2}bc\sin A</m>, which gives <m>\sin A = 2\,\text{Area}/(bc)</m> and hence <m>R = a/(2\sin A) = abc/(4\,\text{Area})</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>The circumcenter</term> is the intersection of the three perpendicular bisectors of the sides. It is equidistant from all three vertices: <m>OA = OB = OC = R</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Circumradius formula:</term>
                        <md>
                            R = \frac{abc}{4 \cdot \text{Area}}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Extended law of sines:</term>
                        <md>
                            \frac{a}{\sin A} = \frac{b}{\sin B} = \frac{c}{\sin C} = 2R.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Right-triangle shortcut:</term> for a right triangle with hypotenuse <m>c</m>,
                        <md>
                            R = \frac{c}{2}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Position of the circumcenter:</term>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>Acute triangle: <m>O</m> is <em>inside</em> the triangle.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Right triangle: <m>O</m> is at the <em>midpoint of the hypotenuse</em>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Obtuse triangle: <m>O</m> is <em>outside</em> the triangle.</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Comparing the Circumcircle and the Incircle</title>
        <p>
            Every triangle has exactly one circumcircle and exactly one incircle. They are different in construction and location:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>incircle</term> is the largest circle that fits <em>inside</em> the triangle, tangent to all three sides. Its centre (the incenter) is always inside the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>circumcircle</term> is the unique circle that passes through all three vertices. Its centre (the circumcenter) is inside the triangle only when the triangle is acute.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            For an equilateral triangle, both circles share the same centre and <m>R = 2r</m> — the circumradius is exactly twice the inradius.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Draw a triangle <m>ABC</m> with <m>AB = 7</m> cm, <m>BC = 5</m> cm, and <m>CA = 6</m> cm. Construct the circumcircle and state the circumradius.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="1.">
                    <li>
                        <p>Draw <m>BC = 5</m> cm as a base. Use compasses to mark <m>AB = 7</m> cm from <m>B</m> and <m>CA = 6</m> cm from <m>C</m>; label the intersection <m>A</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Open the compasses to more than half of <m>AB</m>. Place the point at <m>A</m> and draw arcs above and below <m>AB</m>; repeat from <m>B</m>. Join the two arc intersections — this is the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Repeat the construction for side <m>BC</m>. Label the intersection of the two perpendicular bisectors <m>O</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Set the compasses to <m>OA</m> and draw the circumcircle. It should pass through <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Measuring <m>OA</m> from an accurate drawing gives <m>R \approx 3.4</m> cm. We can verify using the formula: with <m>a = 5</m>, <m>b = 6</m>, <m>c = 7</m>, semi-perimeter <m>s = 9</m>, Heron's formula gives
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \sqrt{9 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2} = \sqrt{216} = 6\sqrt{6} \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>R \amp= \frac{5 \times 6 \times 7}{4 \times 6\sqrt{6}} = \frac{210}{24\sqrt{6}} = \frac{35}{4\sqrt{6}} = \frac{35\sqrt{6}}{24} \approx 3.57 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-5-6-7">
                <caption>Triangle with <m>AB=7</m>, <m>BC=5</m>, <m>CA=6</m> and its circumcircle. The perpendicular bisectors of <m>AB</m> and <m>BC</m> meet at circumcenter <m>O</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 7/0/B}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{6}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{5}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                          \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B)  \tkzGetPoint{MAB}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{MBC}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawLines[gray!55, thin, add=0.6 and 0.6](MAB,O)(MBC,O)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](A,MAB,O)
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.25](B,MBC,O)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$7$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$5$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$6$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>6</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>10</m> cm.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Draw the triangle accurately and construct the circumcircle. Where does the circumcenter fall?</li>
                    <li>Find the circumradius by calculation and compare with your measured value.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-6-8-10">
                <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>6</m> cm and <m>8</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>10</m> cm. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6/0/B, 0/8/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,A,C)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B)(O,C)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$6$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$8$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$10$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                (a) Draw the right triangle with the right angle at one vertex. Construct the perpendicular bisectors of two sides — they meet at <m>O</m>. You should find that <m>O</m> falls exactly at the midpoint of the hypotenuse (<m>10</m> cm side). This confirms the insight: for a right triangle, the circumcenter is always the midpoint of the hypotenuse.
            </p>
            <p>
                (b) Check: <m>6^2 + 8^2 = 36 + 64 = 100 = 10^2</m>, so the hypotenuse is <m>c = 10</m> cm. Using the right-triangle shortcut:
                <md>
                    R = \frac{c}{2} = \frac{10}{2} = 5 \text{ cm.}
                </md>
                Verify with the general formula: Area <m>= \tfrac{1}{2} \times 6 \times 8 = 24</m> cm<m>^2</m>, so
                <md>
                    R = \frac{6 \times 8 \times 10}{4 \times 24} = \frac{480}{96} = 5 \text{ cm.} \checkmark
                </md>
                This should agree with the measured radius from part (a).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangle has sides <m>13</m> cm, <m>14</m> cm, and <m>15</m> cm.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Draw the triangle to scale and construct the circumcircle. Measure the circumradius <m>R</m> from your diagram.</li>
                    <li>Calculate <m>R</m> using the formula and compare with your measured value.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-13-14-15">
                <caption>Triangle with sides <m>13</m> cm, <m>14</m> cm, and <m>15</m> cm and its circumcircle with circumcenter <m>O</m>.</caption>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 14/0/B}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{13}
                          \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{15}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                          \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$14$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$15$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$13$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                (a) Draw the triangle. Construct the perpendicular bisector of the side of length 14 cm and the perpendicular bisector of the side of length 15 cm. Their intersection is <m>O</m>. Draw the circle centred at <m>O</m> through any vertex — it should pass through all three. Measuring <m>R \approx 8.1</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                (b)
                <md>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{13+14+15}{2} = 21 \text{ cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \sqrt{21 \times 8 \times 7 \times 6} = \sqrt{7056} = 84 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>R \amp= \frac{13 \times 14 \times 15}{4 \times 84} = \frac{2730}{336} = \frac{65}{8} = 8.125 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                </md>
                This agrees with the measured value from part (a).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A triangular market plot in Mombasa has boundary lengths <m>5</m> m, <m>12</m> m, and <m>13</m> m. The market committee wants to install a circular fence that runs exactly through all three corners of the plot. Find the radius of the fence.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-circum-5-12-13">
                <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>5</m> m and <m>12</m> m, hypotenuse <m>13</m> m. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 5/0/B, 0/12/C}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                          \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                          %% --- MARK ---
                          \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,A,C)
                          \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B)(O,C)

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$5$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$12$}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$13$}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Check: <m>5^2 + 12^2 = 25 + 144 = 169 = 13^2</m>, so the plot is a right triangle with hypotenuse <m>13</m> m.
                <md>
                    R = \frac{13}{2} = 6.5 \text{ m.}
                </md>
                The circular fence has a radius of <m>6.5</m> m.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a triangle, side <m>BC = 10</m> cm and the circumradius is <m>R = 8</m> cm. Find angle <m>BAC</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                By the extended law of sines, <m>a = 2R\sin A</m>, so
                <md>
                    \sin A = \frac{a}{2R} = \frac{10}{16} = \frac{5}{8}.
                </md>
                Therefore <m>A = \arcsin\!\left(\tfrac{5}{8}\right) \approx 38.7°</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>ABC</m> has <m>AB = 7</m> cm, <m>BC = 8</m> cm, and <m>CA = 6</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle accurately using ruler and compasses.</li>
                        <li>Construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>AB</m>.</li>
                        <li>Construct the perpendicular bisector of <m>BC</m>. Label the intersection <m>O</m>.</li>
                        <li>Draw the circumcircle with centre <m>O</m>. Measure the circumradius <m>R</m>.</li>
                        <li>Check your answer: measure <m>OA</m>, <m>OB</m>, and <m>OC</m>. What do you find?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-6-7-8">
                    <caption>Triangle <m>ABC</m> with <m>AB=7</m> cm, <m>BC=8</m> cm, <m>CA=6</m> cm. Construct the circumcircle.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 7/0/B}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{6}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{8}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                              \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$7$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[right](B,C){$8$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$6$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Construction exercise. For checking: with <m>a=8</m>, <m>b=6</m>, <m>c=7</m>, <m>s=10.5</m>,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp= \sqrt{10.5 \times 2.5 \times 4.5 \times 3.5} = \sqrt{413.4375} \approx 20.33 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>R \amp= \frac{6 \times 7 \times 8}{4 \times 20.33} \approx \frac{336}{81.3} \approx 4.13 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Learners should find <m>OA \approx OB \approx OC \approx R</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has sides <m>9</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm, and <m>15</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle accurately and construct the circumcircle. Before you start: predict where the circumcenter will fall. Explain your prediction.</li>
                        <li>Find the circumradius by calculation and check it matches your diagram.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-9-12-15">
                    <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>9</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>15</m> cm. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.</caption>
                    <image width="60%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B, 0/12/C}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                              %% --- MARK ---
                              \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.35](B,A,C)
                              \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B)(O,C)

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$9$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$12$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$15$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a) Check: <m>9^2+12^2 = 225 = 15^2</m>, so it is a right triangle. The circumcenter should fall at the midpoint of the hypotenuse (15 cm side). After construction, the circumcenter <m>O</m> should indeed be at the midpoint of the hypotenuse.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) <m>R = 15/2 = 7.5</m> cm.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has sides <m>5</m> cm, <m>12</m> cm, and <m>13</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle and construct its circumcircle. Mark the circumcenter <m>O</m> and measure <m>R</m>.</li>
                        <li>Calculate <m>R</m> using the right-triangle shortcut, then verify using <m>R = abc/(4\,\text{Area})</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-5-12-13">
                    <caption>Right triangle with legs <m>5</m> cm and <m>12</m> cm, hypotenuse <m>13</m> cm, and its circumcircle.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 5/0/B, 0/12/C}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                              %% --- MARK ---
                              \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.3](B,A,C)
                              \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](O,B)(O,C)

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$5$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$12$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$13$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a) The triangle is right-angled (<m>5^2+12^2 = 13^2</m>), so <m>O</m> falls at the midpoint of the hypotenuse. Measured <m>R \approx 6.5</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Shortcut: <m>R = 13/2 = 6.5</m> cm. Verify: Area <m>= 30</m> cm<m>^2</m>, <m>R = 5\times12\times13/(4\times30) = 780/120 = 6.5</m> cm. <m>\checkmark</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle has sides <m>7</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>9</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle accurately and construct its circumcircle. Is the circumcenter inside or outside the triangle?</li>
                        <li>Calculate the circumradius, leaving your answer in surd form.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-7-8-9">
                    <caption>Triangle with sides <m>7</m> cm, <m>8</m> cm, and <m>9</m> cm and its circumcircle. The circumcenter <m>O</m> lies inside the triangle.</caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 9/0/B}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rAC}{7}
                              \pgfmathsetmacro{\rBC}{8}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rAC)  \tkzGetPoint{cAC}
                              \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rBC)  \tkzGetPoint{cBC}
                              \tkzInterCC(A,cAC)(B,cBC)  \tkzGetPoints{C}{Cp}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$9$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above right](B,C){$8$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[left](A,C){$7$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a) The triangle is acute (no side satisfies <m>a^2 = b^2 + c^2</m>), so the circumcenter is inside the triangle.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b)
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s \amp= 12, \quad \text{Area} = \sqrt{12 \times 5 \times 4 \times 3} = \sqrt{720} = 12\sqrt{5} \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>R \amp= \frac{7 \times 8 \times 9}{4 \times 12\sqrt{5}} = \frac{504}{48\sqrt{5}} = \frac{21}{2\sqrt{5}} = \frac{21\sqrt{5}}{10} \text{ cm} \approx 4.70 \text{ cm.}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In triangle <m>ABC</m>, <m>BC = 9</m> cm and the circumradius is <m>6</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Find angle <m>BAC</m>.</li>
                        <li>Using your answer to (a) and any valid choice for the other sides, draw a possible triangle <m>ABC</m> and construct its circumcircle. Check that the radius is approximately <m>6</m> cm.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-angle">
                    <caption>An illustrative triangle <m>ABC</m> with side <m>BC = 9</m> cm and circumcircle of radius <m>R = 6</m> cm. Angle <m>A</m> is the inscribed angle subtending <m>BC</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.75]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/B, 9/0/C, 3/8/A}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                              %% --- MARK ---
                              \tkzMarkAngle[arc=l, size=0.7](B,A,C)

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoint[above right](O){$O$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$9$ cm}
                              \tkzLabelAngle[pos=1.1](B,A,C){$A$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a)
                    <md>
                        \sin A = \frac{9}{2 \times 6} = \frac{3}{4}, \qquad A = \arcsin\!\left(\tfrac{3}{4}\right) \approx 48.6°.
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Draw a triangle with <m>BC = 9</m> cm and <m>\angle BAC \approx 48.6°</m> (e.g. use the sine rule or choose suitable side lengths). Construct the circumcircle using perpendicular bisectors; the measured radius should be close to <m>6</m> cm.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    An arbitrary triangle <m>ABC</m> is drawn below. We have created three new triangles <m>\Delta APB</m>, <m>\Delta BQC</m>, <m>\Delta CRA</m>, which are all similar to each other.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles">
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-3/C}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](30:3.8){P}
                                \end{scope}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to C](P) \tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to A](P) \tkzGetPoint{R}

                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)

                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the circumcenter of <m>\Delta ABC</m>, and mark it as <m>O</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles-soln1">
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-3/C}
                                \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                    \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](30:3.8){P}
                                \end{scope}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to C](P) \tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to A](P) \tkzGetPoint{R}

                                \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)

                                \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                \tkzDrawCircle(O,A)

                                \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R,O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C, O)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the circumcenter of <m>\Delta PQR</m>. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The circumcenter of <m>\Delta PQR</m> is the same point <m>O</m> as the circumcenter of <m>\Delta ABC</m>.
                        <figure xml:id="triangle-with-triangles-soln2">
                            <image>
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4/2/B, 5.5/-3/C}
                                        \tkzFindSlopeAngle(A,B)\tkzGetAngle{AngAB}
                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                                        \begin{scope}[rotate=\AngAB]
                                            \tkzDefShiftPoint[A](30:3.8){P}
                                        \end{scope}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to C](P) \tkzGetPoint{Q}
                                        \tkzDefPointBy[rotation with nodes=center O from B to A](P) \tkzGetPoint{R}

                                        \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](P,Q,R) \tkzGetPoint{O'} % This is the same as O


                                        \tkzDrawSegments(A,P P,B B,Q Q,C C,R R,A)
                                        \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=red!20, opacity=0.5](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)
                                        \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=|](B,A,P C,B,Q A,C,R)

                                        \tkzFillAngles[size=0.6, color=blue!20, opacity=0.5](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)
                                        \tkzMarkAngles[size=0.6, mark=||](P,B,A Q,C,B R,A,C)

                                        \tkzDrawCircle(O,A)
                                        \tkzDrawCircle(O',P)

                                        \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,C,P,Q,R,O)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above](P)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[right](Q)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](R)
                                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](A)
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Explain why this happens.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An equilateral triangle has side length <m>12</m> cm.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Draw the triangle and construct both its circumcircle and its incircle. What do you notice about their centres?</li>
                        <li>Calculate the circumradius <m>R</m> and inradius <m>r</m>.</li>
                        <li>Show that <m>R = 2r</m>. How does this match what you see in your diagram?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-circum-exer-equilateral">
                    <caption>Equilateral triangle with side <m>12</m> cm, circumcircle (blue) and incircle (orange). For an equilateral triangle the circumcenter and incenter coincide.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 12/0/B}
                              \tkzDefPointBy[rotation=center A angle 60](B)  \tkzGetPoint{C}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefTriangleCenter[circum](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoint{O}
                              \tkzDefCircle[in](A,B,C)  \tkzGetPoints{I}{Ix}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawPolygon[thick](A,B,C)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[blue!70!black, thick](O,A)
                              \tkzDrawCircle[orange!80!black, thick](I,Ix)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=3pt](A,B,C,O)

                              %% --- MARK ---
                              \tkzMarkSegments[mark=|](A,B)(B,C)(A,C)

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoint[right](O){$O$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below](A,B){$12$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    (a) For an equilateral triangle, the angle bisectors and perpendicular bisectors all coincide, so the incenter and circumcenter are the same point.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area: <m>\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \times 12^2 = 36\sqrt{3}</m> cm<m>^2</m>; semi-perimeter <m>s = 18</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) <m>R = \dfrac{12^3}{4 \times 36\sqrt{3}} = \dfrac{12}{\sqrt{3}} = 4\sqrt{3}</m> cm; <m>r = \dfrac{36\sqrt{3}}{18} = 2\sqrt{3}</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (c) <m>R = 4\sqrt{3} = 2 \times 2\sqrt{3} = 2r</m>. <m>\checkmark</m> In the diagram, the circumcircle's radius is visibly twice the incircle's radius.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

